---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SOCIALS } from '../config';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="My background as a business analyst and why I am moving into product and technical work.">
  <article class="prose prose-zinc max-w-none dark:prose-invert prose-a:text-[var(--color-accent)] prose-headings:[font-family:var(--font-heading)]">
    <h1>About me</h1>

    <p>
      I'm Sean, a business analyst moving into product and technical work.
      For the past few years I've turned ambiguous business problems into
      clear requirements, decisions and outcomes. Now I build the things I
      used to spec.
    </p>

    <h2>Why the pivot</h2>
    <p>
      I chose logistics as my degree out of plain curiosity. Look around the
      room you are in: almost everything in it came from somewhere else in
      the world, carried by an invisible system of ships, ports, trucks and
      schedules. I wanted to know how that system worked, so I studied it.
      Not for the career, for the curiosity.
    </p>
    <p>
      When I entered the workforce, an opportunity came up to move into tech
      through a bootcamp, and the same curiosity lit up again. This time it
      did not stop at understanding the system. I started building, and
      building is addictive in a way analysis never was: a script, a
      calculator, a tool keeps working after you walk away from it. Logistics
      moves things that get delivered and forgotten. Software, built well,
      lasts.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is the pivot. I went from studying the systems that move things to
      building systems that last.
    </p>

    <h2>What I bring from being an analyst</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        I start from the problem, not the solution. Every project on this
        site opens with the problem because that is how I actually work.
      </li>
      <li>
        I verify before I build. The BTO calculator caught two material
        errors in its own spec because I treat requirements as claims to
        check, not instructions to follow.
      </li>
      <li>
        I translate between business and engineering, in both directions,
        without losing what either side actually means.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What I'm learning now</h2>
    <p>
      React and front-end product work, AWS and infrastructure as code
      through projects at work, and the craft of writing case studies that
      show decisions rather than features.
    </p>

    <h2>Get in touch</h2>
    <p>
      The fastest way to reach me is
      {SOCIALS.email ? (
        <a href={`mailto:${SOCIALS.email}`}>email</a>
      ) : (
        <span>email (TODO: add address in src/config.ts)</span>
      )}.
      {SOCIALS.github && (
        <>
          {' '}You can also find my code on{' '}
          <a href={SOCIALS.github} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>.
        </>
      )}
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
